nts leading up to the Reformation. A short essay on how to read historical documents is included. Each reading is preceded by a short introduction and ancillary materials can be found on UTP's History Matters website (www.utphistorymatters.com).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCivilization. 0aHumanismxSourcesxEurope, Northern. 0aHumanism. 0aReformationxSourcesxEurope, Northern. 0aReformation. 0aRenaissancexSourcesxEurope, Northern. 0aRenaissancezEurope, Northern. 0aRenaissance. 4aCoursebook. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh1 aBartlett, Kenneth R. , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcGlynn, Margaret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144260715640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442607156423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442607156/original  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK